            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text is a continuation of the previous text (<htcite0>). Therefore, we recommend studying it before continuing.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0ee05b85-85cb-44a8-a83c-fea5595308e8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Same, but different",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen studying the distance between an object and its image, we place the image on the negative side and perform a subtraction of the values (<htcite0>). Now, imagine that you want to perform operations only on the left side of zero and reflect.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0ee05b85-85cb-44a8-a83c-fea5595308e8",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Same, but different",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: There as here</b><br /><br />Could we use the same rules that we use on the right side of zero also on the left side?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_indigenous",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A Mesoamerican aid\n\nLet us return to an image we have from the site of Copán, in Honduras – America (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblStelaC\"><tr><th>West Side</th><th>East Side</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"><td><img id=\"CWest\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CWest', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaCBeard.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td><td><img id=\"CEast\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CEast', '0%');\" src=\"images/Copan/CopanStelaC.jpg\" style=\"width:50%\" /></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Two sides of Stela C of Copán (<htcite0>). Photos taken on <htdate1>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641",
                     "text": "Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "30"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Table 1** shows, on the left side (west, the direction in which the sun ceases to be visible due to Earth's rotation, i.e., where the sun appears to set), a bearded king. On the right side (east, the direction in which the sun appears due to rotation, i.e., where the sun appears to rise), we see the same king without a beard.\n\nAnalogously, when working with numbers, on the left side we will add a “beard”, represented by the negative sign (-), to indicate the direction we are going. However, as we shall see, the way of performing the operation will not change, as will be presented in the sequence.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_peabiru",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Peabiru\n\nTo better visualize calculations with negative numbers, let us look at a path used by the indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*).\n\nBefore the arrival of the colonizers to the American continent (*Abya Yala*), there was a road that connected the coasts of  *Pindorama*, present-day Brazil (<htcite0>), to *Tawantsuyu*, the Pacific Ocean region controlled by the Incas (<htcite1>). This road is known as the Peabiru and was traversed by Aleixo Garcia in <htdate0> (<htcite2>; <htcite3>), being represented in **Figure 1**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "01b6f0e8-66dc-4afb-b895-9dddd4a7c6dd",
                     "text": "Farias, R.",
                     "page": "pp. 1017",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1997",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ed31f80e-ddd3-448a-9331-a0b6ac5f82fd",
                     "text": "Hechler, R. S.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "035560e0-0a4b-4b81-9df6-6c14cf429e81",
                     "text": "Alomía-Lucero, J. M., & Sixto-Dávila, L.",
                     "page": "pp. 5",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "675460d4-49a0-43ba-baf3-dfa8084e1d28",
                     "text": "de Querejazu, L. E.",
                     "page": "pp. 15 - 17",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1521",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/Mapswire/world-physical-map-graticules-mercator-v1_Peabiru.jpg\" id=\"imgPeabiru\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgPeabiru', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Representation of the Peabiru path followed by Aleixo Garcia. © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>). Shared under the <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Finally, an explanation about **Figure 1**. is necessary. It shows a map in a manner not found in conventional atlases. In this image, we have the Mercator projection with the American continent (*Abya Yala*) at the center of the map.\n\nThis projection was built based on a worldview in which the indigenous peoples of the region are the focus and was inspired by something done by the Jesuit Matteo Ricci in the 17th century, according to the Gregorian calendar, during a trip to China (Zhongguo 中國) (<htcite0>). This fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f521d3c3-2ab8-47c8-85cb-7a26e69db003",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Where is the center?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Mapping</b><br /><br />Would it be possible that the Jesuits made, in Africa and in the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>), the same type of map they made in China (Zhongguo 中國) (<htcite0>)?<br /><br />Can you think of any reason why we are unaware of maps of the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>) from the 17th century, like Matteo Ricci's map?<br /><br />Could there be different interpretations for different peoples?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f521d3c3-2ab8-47c8-85cb-7a26e69db003",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Where is the center?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Ao somar dois números negativos, temos como resultado um número positivo?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Quando somamos dois números negativos, estamos caminhando ainda mais a esquerda, logo não há como eliminarmos o sinal, e por isto o resultado final será à esquerda."
      }
   ],
